---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
---

<Layout 
  title="Cannabis Zoning & Real Estate | Maine Dispensary Guide" 
  description="Finding the right location for your Maine cannabis dispensary. Zoning requirements, lease considerations, and real estate tips."
  heroImage="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1582407947304-fd86f028f716?auto=format&fit=crop&q=80&w=1200&h=400"
>
  <article>
    <div class="article-header">
      <h1>Cannabis Zoning & Real Estate</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Finding the right <a href="/guides/maine-dispensary-locations/">location</a> for your Maine cannabis dispensary</p>
    </div>

    <Callout title="The Reward of the Perfect Spot" type="passion">
      Finding your physical home in the community is one of the most exciting parts of the journey. When you finally unlock the doors to a space that fits your vision, it becomes the foundation where your passion meets your customers every day. It's not just a lease; it's the start of your legacy in the Maine cannabis scene.
    </Callout>

    <section>
      <h2>Overview</h2>
      <p>Finding the right location is one of the most critical decisions for your dispensary. Maine municipalities have significant control over where cannabis businesses can operate. Understanding zoning requirements and <a href="/guides/maine-cannabis-real-estate/">real estate</a> options is essential before signing a lease.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Zoning Fundamentals</h2>
      <p>Maine municipalities can:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Opt-in or opt-out of allowing cannabis businesses</li>
        <li>Designate specific zones for cannabis operations</li>
        <li>Impose additional local requirements</li>
        <li>Set distance requirements from sensitive locations</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Common Zoning Requirements</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Commercial Zoning</strong> - Most dispensaries in commercial or mixed-use zones</li>
        <li><strong>Distance Requirements</strong> - Typically 300-500 ft from schools, churches, playgrounds</li>
        <li><strong>Parking</strong> - Adequate parking required</li>
        <li><strong>Signage</strong> - May have additional restrictions</li>
        <li><strong>Security</strong> - Some towns require security plans</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Finding Properties</h2>
      <h3>Types of Spaces:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Retail Spaces</strong> - Traditional storefronts</li>
        <li><strong>Former Pharmacies</strong> - Good layout, familiar use</li>
        <li><strong>Strip Malls</strong> - Good traffic, shared parking</li>
        <li><strong>Free-Standing Buildings</strong> - More visibility, more cost</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Lease Considerations</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lease Term</strong> - 5+ years recommended</li>
        <li><strong>Build-Out Allowances</strong> - Negotiate tenant improvements</li>
        <li><strong>Exclusivity</strong> - Prevent competitor in same building</li>
        <li><strong>Assignment</strong> - Ability to transfer lease</li>
        <li><strong>Zoning Confirmation</strong> - Verify cannabis-friendly before signing</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Due Diligence</h2>
      <p>Before signing:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Confirm municipality allows cannabis in that zone</li>
        <li>Verify distance from schools, churches</li>
        <li>Check building code compliance</li>
        <li>Review landlord's cannabis policy</li>
        <li>Get estimated build-out costs</li>
        <li>Research traffic patterns and visibility</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Check local zoning before property search</li>
        <li>Verify cannabis allowed in specific zone</li>
        <li>Long-term leases (5+ years) recommended</li>
        <li>Negotiate build-out allowances</li>
        <li>Due diligence is critical before signing</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="external-resources">
      <h2>Further Reading & Resources</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://www.maine.gov/dafs/ocp/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Maine Office of Cannabis Policy (OCP)</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="faq">
      <h2>Extreme FAQ: Real Estate Edition</h2>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Can I set up a dispensary in a converted garage?</summary>
        <p>Maybe, but it's complicated. The property must meet all commercial building codes, OCP security requirements, and local zoning. A converted garage can work if it's structurally sound, meets ADA accessibility requirements, has proper ventilation, and your municipality approves it. Many operators find new construction or purpose-built spaces are actually easier to permit.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Do I need special zoning for a drive-through window?</summary>
        <p>Yes. Drive-through windows require specific zoning approvals that often aren't permitted for cannabis dispensaries in Maine. Some municipalities have banned them entirely due to concerns about youth access and traffic. Even where allowed, you'll need additional parking, a dedicated drive-through lane, and local planning board approval.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>How far must my dispensary be from a school?</summary>
        <p>Maine law requires adult-use cannabis retailers to be at least 500 feet from a school (public or private, K-12). However, some municipalities have imposed stricter distance requirements—some up to 1,000 feet. Always check both state law AND local ordinances before finalizing a location.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Can I lease space in a building that has apartments above?</summary>
        <p>It depends on local zoning and building codes. Many municipalities require complete separation between commercial cannabis operations and residential spaces—meaning separate entrances, separate ventilation systems, and no shared access. Some towns allow vertical mixed-use with strict separation requirements. Check with your local planning office early in your search.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>What happens if my lease is up and the landlord won't renew?</summary>
        <p>This is why long-term leases (5-10 years) with renewal options are critical. If you're month-to-month or have a short lease, you risk losing your location and your license. Maine requires OCP notification of any location change, and relocating triggers a new facility inspection. Plan for stability from day one.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Can I operate out of my home initially?</summary>
        <p>No. Maine regulations require dispensaries to operate in commercial zoned properties. Home-based cannabis businesses are not permitted for retail operations. Even cultivation for personal use has strict limits. Keep your business operations completely separate from any residential property.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Do I need a backup location in my application?</summary>
        <p>OCP doesn't require a backup location, but having one can strengthen your application. It shows planning and reduces concerns about whether you can actually open. Many applicants list their primary location and note that alternative sites have been identified if needed.</p>
      </details>
      
      <details>
        <summary>What about properties with environmental issues?</summary>
        <p>Be very careful with properties that have environmental contamination history (old gas stations, industrial sites, etc.). You'll need Phase I and potentially Phase II environmental assessments, and remediation can be expensive. Also check with your municipality—some have banned dispensaries from former contaminated sites.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

    <section class="disclaimer">
      <p><em><strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only and does not constitute legal or financial advice. Cannabis regulations are subject to change; always consult with the Maine Office of Cannabis Policy and qualified legal counsel.</em></p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  article { max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto; }
  .article-header { margin-bottom: 2rem; padding-bottom: 1.5rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border); }
  .subtitle { font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--color-text-light); }
  section { margin-bottom: 2rem; }
  section h2, section h3 { margin-top: 1.5rem; }
  section h2:first-child { margin-top: 0; }
  table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0; }
  th, td { padding: 0.75rem; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border); }
  th { background: var(--color-background); }
  ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; }
  li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
  .external-resources { margin-top: 3rem; padding-top: 2rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border); }
  .external-resources ul { list-style: none; padding-left: 0; }
  .external-resources li { margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
  .disclaimer { background: #fff3cd; border: 1px solid #ffc107; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 0.5rem; font-size: 0.875rem; margin-top: 2rem; }
</style>
